I love girl talk videos! It‚Äôs so nice to hear people‚Äôs thoughts and opinions on the most mundane things. 

One thing I want to add to the question about marriage you might not have considered! I think you‚Äôre operating under the assumption that people who don‚Äôt get married switch partners and typically aren‚Äôt committed to one person, which in my experience isn‚Äôt the case at all! The reason a lot of people don‚Äôt get married is exactly what you said in the beginning, it has a lot of antiquated origins, but the biggest aspect I think is that people feel like they can have everything a married couple has without the institution of marriage! I definitely think that‚Äôs the case from an emotional and romantic point of view, but from a legal perspective I‚Äôm still undecided. 

For anyone reading this and asking themselves the same question: marriage doesn‚Äôt have to be a romantic or emotional choice and honestly I don‚Äôt think it should be! It can absolutely be just like any other contract you sign. Here are some things you might not have considered about marriage that might help you: Will you be allowed to make medical decisions for your partner? Will you even be allowed in the hospital room outside of visiting hours? How does having kids factor into your decision? Shared finances? Shared businesses? How would it affect home ownership? What about debt? 

I really like the idea of prenups for everyone, not just wealthy people. Divorces are long and messy but with prenups you can set the terms of your marriage + a potential divorce in an official capacity and it can include literally whatever you both want it to include. Depending on what country you get married in and where you‚Äôre filing for divorce, certain laws can really screw you over. After a divorce, can you still be held responsible for debt your spouse created while you were married? 

These are all incredibly important things to consider when you want to decide whether marriage is right for your relationship. You might‚Äôve married your last long term partner if it had worked out between you, but that doesn‚Äôt mean you have to feel the same way about every long term partner. That doesn‚Äôt mean you‚Äôre not committed to the person.

Jenn, have you heard of Postpartum OCD? You'd have to have had OCD your whole life as it's biological, but OCD can be milder and something at some point in your life triggers it to a moderate to severe. OCD isn't just about cleaning and contamination, it can be about any subject. There are compulsions that are mental such as rumination, mental review, checking, neutralizing thoughts. It's different from anxiety in the way the intrusive thoughts just *stick* and are accompanied by *compulsive* debilitating physical or mental behaviors and so many feelings such as guilt feel so loud and unwavering. Just thought I'd share, in case anyone struggles with symptoms, as OCD is so overlooked and misunderstood!

Anxiety is FEAR.
Every single thought will eventually break down and lead back to the core feeling of FEAR.
** example **
I feel bad. I have a cough. 
FEAR starts.
So I have the dreaded virus? If I have the virus, does my child?
Who will care for my child? What if I have to be hospitalised? 
So with all these thoughts we can add to the thought *IF this happens THEN WHAT?*
Ultimately the fear is of dying- me or a child or husband or loved one - then being alone or leaving someone else alone for me.
But the core feeling is always fear of something.
Most of mine end with death or alone. Or same for a loved one.
Once I know the fear it helps to start addressing it.
And for me- I had to one day stop and decide to face it. 
Everything I‚Äôd ever done before was an attempt to calm myself and avoid feeling it I realised. 
I stopped and decided to face it down. I literally talked to it and screamed things like I was in battle and I was .....for my life back.
I said things like BRING IT ON!!!! I cursed it and let it know it will not win me over and I won‚Äôt live this way ANYMORE!

It might help to just start with the IF/THEN concept. Take each thought and add IF that happens THEN.....
The goal being to get to the core fear.
Then work on why that is dominating me.
It also helps for me to break down these further into rational versus irrational. 
Sometimes we get so deep into anxiety that we begin to fear anxiety and panic more than the initial reason we started having it.
So we get stuck.
I hope this may help someone.

Hi Jenn, since you asked and I am a mom of 2 (you liked my comment on another video of yours), I would say you start to establish a routine around the 12 week mark.  That is when your physical recovery is mostly complete (although if you exclusively or mostly breastfeed, you may not get your period until you stop), and you start thinking about how you can't go on like this, sleeping randomly throughout the day and night.  That's also when you start freaking out because some other moms are saying their babies already sleep through the night.  I don't recommend freaking out, but you can start establishing gentle routines and good habits like a bedtime routine, keeping it dark at night even for wakeups and feeds, getting your baby to feed longer during the day and shorter during the night, not necessarily changing every diaper at night to get them back to sleep faster, getting the baby sufficient sunlight during the day to establish their circadian rhythms.  We ended up sleeping training my first around 5 months with a CIO (cry it out) method, whereas never had to for my second because she naturally was more amenable to sleeping without a ton of help at night.  There's always something new though with parenting.  Once you've got the sleep down (kind of--it can take years for some kids), then there's solid foods, sitting, crawling and other milestones, baby proofing, self feeding, potty training, school research.  Haha, the fun never ends!  :)
